#Text=John Barnewall , 3rd Baron Trimlestown
#Text=John Barnewall , 3rd Baron Trimleston
#Text=( died 25 July 1538 ) , was an Irish nobleman , judge and politician .

#Text=He was the eldest son of Christopher Barnewall , 2nd Baron Trimlestown and his wife Elizabeth Plunket , daughter of Sir Thomas Fitz-Christopher Plunket of Rathmore , Lord Chief Justice of the King 's Bench in Ireland and his second wife Marian Cruise .
#Text=He succeeded his father as 3rd Baron about 1513 .
#Text=His ancestors came to Ireland originally with Henry II and received large grants of land in County Cork .
#Text=However , at the first favourable opportunity the old proprietors , the O'Sullivans , rose and murdered the whole family save one young man , who was absent studying law in England .
#Text=He ultimately returned to Ireland and settled at Drimnagh , near Dublin .
#Text=Biography
#Text=The subject of our sketch rose to high office in Ireland under Henry VIII ; he was knighted around 1513 , and received grants of land near Dunleer .
#Text=He was unusual among the Irish nobility in his time both in his legal ability and his willingness to hold judicial office .
#Text=O'Flanagan suggests that in becoming a judge he wished to follow the distinguished example of his maternal grandfather , Chief Justice Plunket .

#Text=He was made Attorney General for Ireland in 1504 , Solicitor General for Ireland and King 's Sergeant shortly after , a justice of the Court of King 's Bench in 1514 , Deputy Treasurer and then Lord Treasurer of Ireland in 1524 and Lord Chancellor of Ireland in 1534 .

#Text=O'Flanagan praises him as an expert on finance as well as law , but adds somewhat cynically that his greatest talent was for looking after his own interests , as evidenced by the substantial grants of lands at Dunleer made to him by the English Crown . [ 1 ] [ 2 ] [ 3 ]

#Text=In 1536 , under the command of the Lord Treasurer , Sir William Brabazon , he made an incursion into Offaly , and drove back the O'Conor clan , who were then ravaging the Anglo-Irish settlements .
#Text=The next year , commissioned by the Privy Council of Ireland , he negotiated successfully with the O'Neills .

#Text=During the Rebellion of Silken Thomas , he was one of the Irish nobles whose loyalty to the Crown was considered to dubious , but it seems that these suspicions were not strong enough for any action to be taken against him .
#Text=He died on 25 July 1538 .
#Text=Family
#Text=He was four times married . [ 4 ]

#Text=Only the names of his first and second wives are known for certain : they were Janet ( or Genet ) Bellew of Bellewstown , and Margaret , daughter of Patrick FitzLeones , who was three times Lord Mayor of Dublin between 1477 and 1495 ; her mother was a member of the influential FitzEustace family .
#Text=He had at least three children-
#Text=Patrick Barnewall , 4th Baron Trimlestown .
#Text=Elizabeth Barnewall , who married three times : her husbands were George Plunkett , Christopher Eustace and William Darcy .
#Text=Catherine Barnewall , who married Patrick Hussey , Baron Galtrim , and had four children , including James , Baron Galtrim , and Mary , who married Oliver Plunkett . [ 5 ]
#Text=Patrick Barnewall
#Text=, Solicitor General for Ireland and Master of the Rolls in Ireland , was his nephew , the son of his sister Alison who married their cousin Roger Barnewall of Kingsland .
